thetic: ‘drone imaginary’, a prism of cultural and critical knowledge, through which the complex interplay between drone technology and human communities is explored, and from which its historical, cultural and political dimensions can be assessed.The contributors offer diverse approaches to this interdisciplinary field of aesthetic drone imaginaries. With essays on the aesthetic configurations of drone swarming, historical perspectives on early unmanned aviation, as well as current debates on how drone technology alters the human body and creates new political imaginaries, this book provides new insights to the rapidly evolving field of drone studies. Working across art history, literature, photography, feminism, postcolonialism and cultural studies, Drone imaginaries offers a unique insight into how drones are changing our societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAerial photographyxSocial aspects. 0aDrone aircraftxSocial aspects. 0aTechnology and civilization. 4aPolitical Studies 2022. 70(DE-588)4035964-50(DE-627)1062450150(DE-576)209015608aLiteratur2gnd 70(DE-588)4059205-40(DE-627)1044096060(DE-576)209129956aTechnik2gnd 70(DE-588)4114333-40(DE-627)1058229570(DE-576)209483733aKunst2gnd 70(DE-588)4125698-00(DE-627)1044703480(DE-576)209578750aKultur2gnd 70(DE-588)4125909-90(DE-627)1057364220(DE-576)209580607aMensch-Maschine-Kommunikation2gnd 70(DE-588)4322103-80(DE-627)1279967450(DE-576)211233919aUnbemanntes Flugzeug2gnd 70(DE-588)4332556-70(DE-627)1480509480(DE-576)211332755aDrohnegFlugkörper2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aaerial technology.  aaesthetics.  aautomation.  acommunities.  acultural studies.  adrones.  ahuman-machine interaction.  aimaginaries.  aremote warfare.  asurveillance.1 aBraeunert, Svea, econtributor.4c